andal%20sword%20is%20popularly%20known%20as%20the%20French%20Excalibur%2C%20referring%20to%20the%20sword%20King%20Arthur%20pulled%20from%20stone%20as%20%26quot%3Bthe%20true%20king%26quot%3B%20of%20Britain.%20According%20to%20legend%2C%20an%20angel%20gave%20the%20sword%20to%20Holy%20Roman%20emperor%20Charlemagne%20in%20the%20eighth%20century.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWhile%20it%20is%20not%20known%20what%20led%20to%20the%20mysterious%20vanishing%20of%20the%20weapon%2C%20locals%20believe%20it%20was%20stolen%20by%20a%20thief%20who%20likely%20pulled%20it%20out%20of%20the%20rock%20wall%20it%20was%20wedged%20into%2C%20some%20100%20feet%20above%20ground.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAn%2011th-century%20poem%2C%20that%20talks%20of%20the%20'magic%20capabilities'%20of%20the%20sword%2C%20is%20the%20oldest%20surviving%20work%20of%20French%20literature.%20The%20only%20surviving%20copy%20of%20%E2%80%9CThe%20Song%20of%20Roland%26quot%3B%20is%20now%20housed%20at%20the%20Bodleian%20Library%20in%20Oxford.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20sword%20and%20the%20legend%20surrounding%20it%20were%20one%20of%20the%20town's%20main%20attractions.%20If%20the%20town%20stories%20are%20to%20be%20believed%2C%20the%20indestructible%20sword%20could%20cut%20through%20stone%20with%20a%20single%20blow.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ELegend%20says%20King%20Charlemagne%20gifted%20the%20magic%20sword%20to%20his%20best%20soldier%2C%20Roland%2C%20an%20elite%20knight.%20Before%20he%20died%20in%20battle%2C%20Roland%20attempted%20to%20destroy%20the%20sword%20so%20his%20enemies%20could%20not%20use%20it%20but%20was%20unable%20to%20break%20it.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%3E%3Cimg%20alt%3D%5C%22Knight%20Roland%20with%20his%20sword%20at%20the%20Battle%20of%20Roncevaux%20Pass%20(Photo%20Credit%3A%20ancient-origins.net)%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Knight%20Roland%20with%20his%20sword%20at%20the%20Battle%20of%20Roncevaux%20Pass%20(Photo%20Credit%3A%20ancient-origins.net)%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fc.ndtvimg.com%2F2024-07%2Fi9hrjvvg_d